---
import Layout from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Nav from "../components/Nav.astro";
import PostTrainingExplorer from "../components/PostTrainingExplorer.jsx";
import { postTrainingReferences, postTrainingValueModes } from "../lib/learning-content.js";
---

<Layout
  title="Human Feedback Value"
  description="An explorer for how human data value flows through reinforcement learning-based post-training."
>
  <style>
    .post-page {
      display: grid;
      gap: 2.4rem;
    }

    .post-header {
      max-width: var(--measure);
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }

    .post-prose {
      max-width: var(--measure);
    }

    .post-stub-note {
      max-width: var(--measure);
      padding: 1rem 0;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    }

    .post-stub-note h2 {
      margin: 0 0 0.65rem;
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: clamp(1.45rem, 2vw, 1.9rem);
      line-height: 1.08;
      letter-spacing: 0;
    }

    .post-stub-note p {
      margin: 0 0 0.9rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      line-height: 1.78;
    }

    .post-stub-note p:last-child {
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }

    .post-explorer-frame {
      padding-top: 1rem;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
    }

    .post-mode-list,
    .post-reference-list {
      list-style: none;
      margin: 0;
      padding: 0;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      max-width: var(--measure);
    }

    .post-mode-list li,
    .post-reference-list li {
      padding: 1rem 0;
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
    }

    .post-mode-list h3,
    .post-reference h3 {
      margin: 0 0 0.35rem;
      font-family: var(--font-display);
      font-size: 1.25rem;
      line-height: 1.12;
      letter-spacing: 0;
    }

    .post-mode-list p,
    .post-reference p {
      margin: 0;
      color: var(--muted);
      font-family: var(--font-ui);
      font-size: 0.94rem;
      line-height: 1.65;
    }

    .post-reference {
      color: inherit;
      text-decoration: none;
    }

    .post-reference:hover h3,
    .post-reference:focus-visible h3 {
      color: var(--ring-thick);
    }

    .post-reference:focus-visible {
      outline: var(--focus-outline);
      outline-offset: 4px;
    }

    .post-formula {
      max-width: var(--measure);
      padding-top: 1rem;
      border-top: 1px solid var(--border);
      color: var(--muted);
      line-height: 1.75;
    }

    .post-formula code {
      display: block;
      margin-top: 0.45rem;
      overflow-x: auto;
      color: var(--fg);
      white-space: nowrap;
    }
  </style>

  <Nav />

  <main class="page post-page" id="main-content" tabindex="-1">
    <header class="page-header post-header">
      <h1 class="page-title">Human Feedback Value</h1>
      <p class="page-lede">
        This page is a stub for a future module about how human data value flows through
        reinforcement learning-based post-training.
      </p>
    </header>

    <div class="section-copy post-prose">
      <p>
        The existing grid asks what happens when training or evaluation subsets change. Post-training
        data value often moves through a sequence instead: demonstrations, preference comparisons,
        reward modeling, policy optimization, red-team loops, deployment feedback, and future access.
        Primary examples of preference data feeding a reward model and later policy optimization include
        <a href="https://proceedings.neurips.cc/paper/2020/hash/1f89885d556929e98d3ef9b86448f951-Abstract.html">Stiennon et al. (2020)</a>
        and <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.02155">Ouyang et al. (2022)</a>.
      </p>
      <p>
        There are useful methods for narrower parts of this problem: supervised-data valuation,
        LLM data attribution, preference learning, and emerging work on sequential or
        structure-aware valuation. But this site treats the cross-stage version as an open problem.
        Our review did not identify a generally accepted, well-calibrated method for putting these values on a
        fully exchangeable scale across pretraining data, supervised fine-tuning data, preference
        data, reward-model data, evaluation traces, and later deployment feedback. Even within
        post-training, multiple steps can interact in ways that make simple attribution hard. See
        <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2307.15217">Casper et al. (2023)</a> for a survey of open problems and limitations in RLHF more broadly.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="post-stub-note" aria-labelledby="post-stub-title">
      <h2 id="post-stub-title">Status: stub and mockup.</h2>
      <p>
        The worked example below uses made-up numbers. It is only a sketch of the kinds of quantities
        a future explorer might display, not a calibrated valuation method and not evidence about any
        real RLHF pipeline.
      </p>
      <p>
        To make this rigorous, we would need much better dataset documentation, transparency about
        post-training data mixtures and workflows, provenance and licensing records, attribution
        methods for staged training pipelines, and interpretability or auditing tools that connect
        feedback sources to model behavior. The hope is to calibrate this kind of demo once the
        relevant calibration data exist.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="post-explorer-frame" aria-label="Human feedback value explorer">
      <PostTrainingExplorer client:load />
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="post-modes-title">
      <h2 class="section-title" id="post-modes-title">What we want to understand</h2>
      <ul class="post-mode-list">
        {postTrainingValueModes.map((mode) => (
          <li>
            <article>
              <h3>{mode.title}</h3>
              <p>{mode.body}</p>
            </article>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="post-formal-title">
      <h2 class="section-title" id="post-formal-title">Why this is harder than a grid cell</h2>
      <div class="section-copy post-prose">
        <p>
          A simple grid cell compares one training world and one evaluation world. A post-training
          counterfactual compares two feedback pipelines while holding the base model, task mix, and
          policy-update recipe as fixed as possible. That is a useful conceptual object, but it is
          not yet a plug-and-play measurement recipe.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="post-formula">
        One compact way to name the object:
        <code>Compare(U(PostTrain(M_base, H'), E), U(PostTrain(M_base, H), E))</code>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section aria-labelledby="post-reference-title">
      <h2 class="section-title" id="post-reference-title">Reference points</h2>
      <ul class="post-reference-list">
        {postTrainingReferences.map((reference) => (
          <li>
            <a class="post-reference" href={reference.href}>
              <h3>{reference.title}</h3>
              <p>{reference.body}</p>
            </a>
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
    </section>
  </main>
</Layout>
